{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4ce73186-273a-4c81-98e7-11e7ddeb4dbf","content":"The project doesn't exist at that path in this workspace, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport:\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"${workspaceFolder}/src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`dotnet run --project`** — builds and launches your server.\n- Your MCP server must read JSON-RPC from **stdin** and write responses to **stdout** (no `Console.WriteLine` for logging — use **stderr** instead).\n\nIf you publish the server as a standalone executable, you can point `command` directly at the binary and drop the `args`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ca7a30ec-3f8c-4340-98ad-b48d4187f884","outputTokens":264,"requestId":"F3D1:19AB05:11A863:15DF0B:69F54DE6"},"id":"1caa594d-440b-4fed-a915-5740b152f40d","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:05:49.254Z","parentId":"f3976525-66af-4e1a-9b08-a04b2d7f3df7"}
